# Product UX + Data Consistency

- Keep primary user action prominent on each page (for Expenses page: adding expense first).
- Secondary/advanced sections should be collapsible with clear affordance (label + chevron) and smooth expand/collapse animation.
- Avoid native browser confirmations (`alert/confirm/prompt`) for product flows; use in-app modal dialogs.
- Every clickable UI entity must show pointer cursor (`cursor-pointer` or equivalent).
- Provide explicit success/error toast feedback for user-triggered mutations (create/update/delete/archive/process).
- After API calls or user actions that require acknowledgement, always show a clear toast outcome (success, info, warning, or error as appropriate), and avoid duplicate toasts for the same event.
- Validation UX must not break layout; reserve message space to avoid shift/distortion.
- For money display in this app, always use INR with Indian locale formatting (`en-IN`, `currency: "INR"`).
- Category names are case-insensitive for uniqueness (`groceries` == `Groceries`).
- Normalize category display names to Title Case before save (e.g., `groceries` -> `Groceries`).
- For create flows like Accounts, always acknowledge successful creation with a success toast (not only inline state changes).
- Treat entity names (accounts/categories and similar user-defined names) as case-insensitive for uniqueness; block duplicates in both UI validation and mutation/data layer checks.
- Apply duplicate checks at both UI and mutation/data layer where feasible.
- Keep behavior and copy consistent across similar flows (delete/archive/settle/payment confirmations and toasts).
- Prefer reusable shared utilities/providers for cross-cutting behavior (confirm provider, formatters, normalization helpers).
- Use professional, production-grade microcopy across UI labels/placeholders/tooltips; avoid casual/personal examples (e.g., person names or slang).
- Placeholder examples must be domain-relevant and professional (e.g., `Primary Bank Account`, `Vendor Advance Account`, `Apartment Rent`), not informal text.
- If any CTA is disabled, always provide a clear reason via tooltip, helper text, or inline hint (do not leave disabled actions unexplained).
- For disabled actions, include accessible guidance as well (`title`, `aria-describedby`, or equivalent) so users can understand what to do next.
